		</table></td><td class="PanelBodyAlternate" valign="Top"><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="3" border="0" width="100%">
			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Soloing,  what's your motivation?<a name="35995"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Apr 22 04 5:22 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>The number one (#1) reason why I choose to solo in a MMORPG is that I get to see more areas of the game then I ever would by grouping.
<br />

<br />
I'm not sure if I can explain it fully, but because I have nothing else to do for the next half hour I'll try. <img src="/skins/default/images/emotions/emotion-4.gif" border="0" alt="Tongue out" hspace="2" />
<br />

<br />
For the most part EQ has always been (IMHO) a game dedicated to camping a few select zones.  Those zones were the ones that had the best loot table or provided the best experiance modifier.  Generally speaking, if someone was seeking a group they would most most likely be found in those select zones.
<br />

<br />
As EQ grew folks began moving to the zones that offered better loot and exp then the old ones.  It was a natural progression.  Most of the time you still spent alot of it traveling to those places and then more of it waiting for a group to respond to your /ooc or /shout LFG.  SSDD.
<br />

<br />
Trying to get your friends to leave those zones that eventually provided a group (for the most part) to explore (travel) to an out of the way place was diffucult to say the least.  If you (or one of your friends) didn't know the new area, then you could pretty much forget going there.
<br />

<br />
Also, if you did by chance get some of your friends to go with you to an out of the way place, then once you logged back on the next day they were back in the more populated zones.  Over time this gets annoying.  Unless you get lucky enough to find 5 other folks (out of some 4,000 sharing your server) with the same spirit of exploration, then you were back with them in Dreadlands killing stupid drovlargs (or whatever).
<br />

<br />
Grouping is almost the same now as it was way back when.  You're still going to find your groups located in the places that has the drops (loot) everyone wants, coupled with a good exp modifier for the zone.  How many folks (including those who are old school) can really say that they have traveled completely through the sewers in Qeynos or Freeport?  Did anyone ever kill every mob in Kedge Keep (aside for what were then raid mobs)?  Does anyone know the way to get from Paineel to The Temple of Veeshen without getting a port or using PoK (not saying everyone should here either)?
<br />

<br />
Through soloing, I can honestly say yes to these questions and tell you a pretty funny story about something that happened in every zone along the way.  Overall, I tend to picture folks that do not group as pioneers of EQ.  While they are not always the first to see a new place, they are usually the ones that can tell you the most about it.
<br />

<br />
If I had to name a second reason for soloing in a MMORPG, it would be for less competition of content and loot.  I still get annoyed (if I think about it too long) of all the groups I've been in where the group was trianed by another so they could have our spot.  I would rather be killing a hermit in South Karana getting my fine steel weapon and 2pp every 5 kills then be in Paludal Caverns where the shout of train can be heard every 4 minutes.
<br />

<br />
The simple answer to this though would be LDoN, but I've already learned something one way.  By now it is such a big part to the way I play, to really change now is difficult to say the least.
<br />

<br />
One last thing and then I'll end this boring post (yeah! <img src="/skins/default/images/emotions/emotion-2.gif" border="0" alt="Big Smile" hspace="2" /> ).  If someone was to do a little digging around (like become an in game street reporter) by asking folks they see soloing today, <b>I</b> think that person would find that more then 75% of them would say the character they are playing was not their first one.  The next thing they would say (if asked) would be that their first character was group dependant and they just wanted a change from having to depend on other folks.
<br />

<br />
For what it is worth, there's my 2cp.</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
